[{:rule-id "clojure", :item {:feed-id "planet-clojure", :item-id "https://www.bigconfig.ai/blog/the-vibecoder-stack-astro-pocketbase-docker-once-bigconfig/", :title "The Vibecoder Stack: Astro, PocketBase, Docker, ONCE, and BigConfig", :link "https://www.bigconfig.ai/blog/the-vibecoder-stack-astro-pocketbase-docker-once-bigconfig/", :published-at #inst "2026-05-09T00:00:00.000-00:00", :content "Every generation of developers has its stack. The 2000s had LAMP. The 2010s had MEAN and JAMstack. The Vibecoder—the developer who ships software through plain-English prompts—needs a stack that is small enough for an LLM to reason about end-to-end, yet expressive enough to ship a real product. After a year of building and rebuilding agentic workflows, I keep landing on the same five pieces. I call it the Vibecoder Stack: Astro — the frontend PocketBase — the backend Docker — the artifact ONCE — the deployment philosophy BigConfig — the agentic package manager Five layers, one container, zero dashboards. Let’s walk through each one. 1. Astro — The Frontend the Agent Already Knows Astro is a content-first web framework that ships zero JavaScript by default and lets you sprinkle in React, Svelte, or Vue islands when you need them. For a Vibecoder, Astro hits a sweet spot: Static-first. The build artifact is a folder of HTML, CSS, and tiny JS bundles. Predictable to host, trivial to cache. MDX everywhere. The content layer is Markdown with components. An agent can author, edit, and refactor pages without touching a parser. Tiny mental model. A page is a file. A route is a path. There is no opinion to push back against. The Astro project I deploy is small enough that Claude Code can hold the entire src/ tree in context and refactor it confidently. That property—LLM-fits-in-context—is the real selection criterion for the frontend. 2. PocketBase — The Backend in a Single Binary PocketBase is a single Go binary that gives you SQLite, auth, realtime subscriptions, file storage, and an admin UI. One binary. One file on disk. One mental model. ./pocketbase serve --http=0.0.0.0:8090 That’s the whole backend. For a Vibecoder this is a gift: No ORM, no migrations framework, no schema-as-code ceremony. The schema lives in the SQLite file, evolved through the admin UI or the JS/Go SDKs. Auth is built in. OAuth2, password, email verification, password reset—done. It’s a database. Backups are cp pb_data.db backup.db. Restores are the reverse. A human or an agent can reason about that. When the backend is a single binary with a single data file, the agent doesn’t hallucinate Kubernetes manifests. It runs the binary. 3. Docker — The Universal Envelope Astro builds to static files. PocketBase is a binary. The glue is a multi-stage Dockerfile that bakes both into a single image and exposes a single port. Dockerfile FROM node:22-alpine AS frontend RUN corepack enable && corepack prepare pnpm@latest --activate WORKDIR /app COPY package.json pnpm-lock.yaml ./ RUN pnpm install --frozen-lockfile COPY . . RUN pnpm build \n FROM alpine:3.20 AS backend RUN apk add --no-cache curl unzip ARG PB_VERSION=0.22.21 RUN curl -L https://github.com/pocketbase/pocketbase/releases/download/v${PB_VERSION}/pocketbase_${PB_VERSION}_linux_arm64.zip \\       -o /tmp/pb.zip \\     && unzip /tmp/pb.zip -d /usr/local/bin/ \\     && rm /tmp/pb.zip \n FROM alpine:3.20 RUN apk add --no-cache ca-certificates COPY --from=backend  /usr/local/bin/pocketbase /usr/local/bin/pocketbase COPY --from=frontend /app/dist                 /pb_public EXPOSE 80 VOLUME [\"/pb_data\"] CMD [\"pocketbase\", \"serve\", \"--http=0.0.0.0:80\", \\      \"--publicDir=/pb_public\", \"--dir=/pb_data\"] PocketBase serves the Astro build out of /pb_public and persists state in /pb_data. The whole product is now a single OCI image you can push to GHCR and pull anywhere. Health checks live at /api/health. 4. ONCE — The Deployment Philosophy ONCE is 37signals’ idea that an application should be installed once, on your server, with your data, and then run forever. No SaaS subscription, no multi-tenant control plane, no per-seat pricing. The Vibecoder Stack adopts the same philosophy: One image, one VPS, one domain. State on disk, not in someone else’s region. Upgrades are docker pull && docker run, not migrations of a fleet. The constraint is liberating. Because we are not building a multi-tenant SaaS, we don’t need Kubernetes, service meshes, or autoscalers. A 4-core, 24 GB Oracle Always-Free instance—or a €4/month Hetzner box—is plenty. The hard part of ONCE is no longer the app. It’s the last mile: a VPS with a public IP, DNS pointing at it, TLS, and SMTP for transactional email. That’s where layer five comes in. 5. BigConfig — The Infrastructure Glue BigConfig is a Clojure-based infrastructure package manager. It exposes high-level packages—reusable, validated workflows—instead of raw Terraform or Ansible. The once package wires up the last mile of an ONCE deployment: Compute — Hetzner, Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, DigitalOcean. DNS — Cloudflare records and zone management. SMTP — Resend domain verification and API keys. SSH — auto-populated ~/.ssh/config so ssh once just works. git clone https://github.com/bigconfig-ai/once cd once bb once create     # provision VPS + DNS + SMTP ssh once           # log in sudo once          # launch the ONCE TUI to install the image Three commands. From a blank cloud account to a live URL. Because BigConfig is a library consumed via Babashka tasks—not a binary CLI with hidden state—every step is transparent, version-controllable, and reversible. An agent can read the configuration, propose an edit, and re-run it. That’s the property that makes BigConfig agent-friendly: the configuration is data, not magic. Why These Five, Together? Each piece of the stack is independently good. The reason they belong together is that they share a single property: the entire system fits in an LLM’s context window. Layer Surface area an agent must understand Astro A folder of MDX and a handful of components PocketBase One binary, one SQLite file, one admin UI Docker A 30-line Dockerfile ONCE One image, one server, one domain BigConfig A bb.edn and an .envrc When the agent can hold the whole system in its head, hallucinations collapse. The agent stops inventing Kubernetes operators because there are none to invent. It stops guessing Terraform parameters because the BigConfig package has already validated them. This is the inversion that matters: instead of giving the agent more powerful tools, we give it a smaller world. A small, deterministic, well-typed world is the best prompt-engineering trick we have. The Workflow End-to-End Here is what shipping a new feature looks like on the Vibecoder Stack: You describe the feature to Claude Code in plain English. The agent edits Astro pages and PocketBase collections. pnpm build produces the static frontend; the Dockerfile bakes it into the image. A GitHub Action pushes the image to GHCR on every commit to main. bb once create (first time only) provisions the VPS, DNS, and SMTP via BigConfig. sudo once on the server pulls the new image and restarts the container. No dashboards. No YAML pipelines longer than the program itself. No SaaS bill that grows with your traffic. What This Stack Is Not It is not for everyone, and that’s the point. Not for multi-tenant SaaS at scale. PocketBase + a single VPS is a beautiful constraint until you hit it. If you’re serving millions of tenants, this is the wrong stack. Not for teams that love managed databases. If you want RDS with point-in-time recovery, this stack will feel primitive. The trade is sovereignty for convenience. Not a framework for legacy migration. It’s a greenfield stack. Plant new things in it; don’t try to retrofit a 10-year-old monolith. What it is very good at: turning a Vibecoder’s prompt into a production URL, with state, auth, email, and TLS, in an afternoon. Conclusion The Vibecoder Stack is what happens when you stop optimizing for what humans can scale and start optimizing for what an LLM can reason about. Astro keeps the frontend tiny. PocketBase keeps the backend in a single binary. Docker turns the pair into one artifact. ONCE keeps the deployment philosophy honest. BigConfig closes the last mile. Five layers. One container. Zero dashboards. If you want to see the whole thing in action, browse the BigConfig Marketplace —it is itself a Vibecoder Stack app, deployed by the very once package it catalogs. Turtles, all the way down. Would you like a follow-up on this topic? I’d love to hear what you’d build on it."}, :excerpts [{:text "... is a content-first web framework that ships zero JavaScript by default and lets you sprinkle in React,...", :matched-terms ["java"], :source :content} {:text "... — The Infrastructure Glue BigConfig is a Clojure-based infrastructure package manager. It exposes...", :matched-terms ["clojure"], :source :content} {:text "... # launch the ONCE TUI to install the image Three commands. From a blank cloud a", :matched-terms ["command"], :source :content}]}]